\begin_layout Standard
There is a large population, whose members have a single genetic trait 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}$
\end_inset

 and a single social trait 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 These are random variables which may be discrete or mixed and may also
 be correlated.
 Couples match and have children: we write 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{p}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{p}$
\end_inset

 for the parents' generation, 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{c}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{c}$
\end_inset

 for the children's generation, and drop the subscripts for statements which
 apply to both.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Couples match randomly among individuals of the same 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

attractiveness
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=a(G,S)=(1-k)f(G)+kv(S)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 are continuous increasing functions.
 Without loss of generality, we measure 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

attractiles
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=(1-k)G+kS.
\]

\end_inset

We also scale them so that 
\begin_inset Formula $EG_{p}=ES_{p}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Var(G_{p})=Var(S_{p})=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B=kG-(1-k)S.
\]

\end_inset

This is orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 It can be thought of as the relative weight of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Beauty
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Brains
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in making someone attractive.
 We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Var(B_{p}|A_{p})>0\textrm{ for a set of values of \ensuremath{A_{p}} of positive measure.}\label{eq:pos-var-B-given-A}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $EA_{p}=EB_{p}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Recall that if 
\begin_inset Formula $EX=EY=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Var(X)=EX^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Cov(X,Y)=EXY$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Couples have two children each, and children's value of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is equal to the mean of their parents.
 As a result, children have the same value of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 as both their parents.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now prove that the correlation between genetic endowment and social status
 is higher in the children's generation, so long as 
\begin_inset Formula $0<k<1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
PROPOSITION 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset Formula $0<k<1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Corr(G_{c},S_{c})>Corr(G_{p},S_{p})$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Corr(G_{c},S_{c})=Corr(G_{p},S_{p})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
PROOF
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rearranging the equations gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
S & =cA-dB,\\
G & =dA+cB
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
c & \equiv\frac{k}{z},\label{eq:def-cd}\\
d & \equiv\frac{1-k}{z},\textrm{ and}\nonumber \\
z & \equiv k^{2}+(1-k)^{2}.\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

 We calculate the covariance of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 in terms of the new variables:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
Cov(G,S) & =E(GS)\nonumber \\
 & =E(dA+cB)(cA-dB)\nonumber \\
 & =E(cdA^{2}+(c^{2}-d^{2})AB-cdB^{2})\nonumber \\
 & =cd\ [Var(A)-Var(B)]+(c^{2}-d^{2})Cov(A,B)\label{eq:cov-G-S}
\end{align}

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $EA=EB=EG=ES=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we note that since children's 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is equal to parents' 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Var(A_{p})=Var(A_{c}),\label{eq:var-A-same}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and indeed the whole distribution is the same:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Pr(A_{p}=a)=Pr(A_{c}=a)\textrm{ for all }a.\label{eq:dist-A-same}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, note that for every value of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E(B_{c}|A)=E(B_{p}|A),\label{eq:E-b-given-a-same}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

since within each pair, the children's value of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is equal to the parents' mean.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lastly, for every value of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, the children's 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the mean of two random draws from 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 given 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Var(B_{c}|A)=\frac{1}{2}Var(B_{p}|A).\label{eq:cond-var-B-less}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Applying the law of total variance to 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, and using (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:cond-var-B-less"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:E-b-given-a-same"

\end_inset

), along with (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pos-var-B-given-A"

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
question, if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are orthogonal then shouldn't the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

explained variance
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $Var(E(B_{c}|A))=0$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
But NB, 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 being independent doesn't guarantee independence of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, not even mean-independence I think.
 Maybe for normal distribution
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
Var(B_{c}) & =E_{A}(Var(B_{c}|A))+Var(E(B_{c}|A))\label{eq:var-B-less}\\
 & <E_{A}(Var(B_{p}|A))+Var(E(B_{p}|A))=Var(B_{p}).\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rewrite
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
 & Cov(A,B)\\
= & \int\int ab\ Pr(a)Pr(b|a)\ \textrm{d}b\ \textrm{d}a\\
= & \int a\ Pr(a)\int bPr(b|a)\ \textrm{d}b\ \textrm{d}a\\
= & \int a\ Pr(a)E(B|A)\ \textrm{d}a.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dist-A-same"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:E-b-given-a-same"

\end_inset

) then shows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Cov(A_{p},B_{p})=Cov(A_{c},B_{c}).\label{eq:cov-A-B-same}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Plugging facts (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:var-B-less"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:cov-A-B-same"

\end_inset

) into the expression in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:cov-G-S"

\end_inset

), we have shown
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Cov(G_{p},S_{p})= & cd[Var(A_{p})-Var(B_{p})]+(c^{2}-d^{2})Cov(A_{p},B_{p})\\
\le & cd[Var(A_{c})-Var(B_{c})]+(c^{2}-d^{2})Cov(A_{c},B_{c})\\
= & Cov(G_{c},S_{c}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The inequality is strict when 
\begin_inset Formula $cd$
\end_inset

 is positive, equivalently when 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

, and holds with equality otherwise.
 The covariance and correlation share the same sign, so this completes the
 proof.
\end_layout

